Parkinson's disease (PD) is a common disease of older adults. It presents a 
unique set of anesthetic challenges. With increasing life expectancy and the 
rapid growth of oldest-old patients, it is now more likely for anesthesiologists 
to encounter older patients with PD. Due to polypharmacy in the older adults 
with PD a potential for drug interactions during and after surgery needs to be 
considered. More data from prospective, multicenter trials about short- and 
long-term outcomes of anesthesia in PD patients are needed.

